      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20
One question that might be important is: How much is Twitter Inc. worth if =
Elon Musk does=C2=A0not=C2=A0buy it? If Twitter announced today =E2=80=9Cwe=
 have agreed to terminate our deal with Elon Musk with no money changing ha=
nds, never mind,=E2=80=9D what would happen to the stock? Well, it would go=
 down.=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know how much. But just to put a number on it, =
let=E2=80=99s assume that it would trade to $25 per share,=C2=A0that that i=
s Twitter=E2=80=99s stand-alone value.[1] That is not investing advice or e=
ven a real estimate, but it=E2=80=99s helpful to have a placeholder.At Musk=
=E2=80=99s $54.20 deal price, Twitter is worth about $44 billion; at $25 it=
 would be worth about $20 billion. The difference is $24 billion, or $29.20=
 per share. Musk is paying $24 billion over Twitter=E2=80=99s stand-alone v=
alue. Or he isn=E2=80=99t. In April he agreed to pay $44 billion to buy Twi=
tter; last Friday he announced that he will try to get out of the deal. We =
 talked about this on Saturday.Note that Twitter should, in theory, be indi=
fferent between (1) closing the deal and (2) getting a check from Musk=C2=
=A0for $24 billion. If Musk paid Twitter the $24 billion=C2=A0difference in=
 cash, Twitter could pay it out as a dividend to its shareholders. Instead =
of having $54.20 in cash, they=E2=80=99d have $29.20 in cash and a share of=
 stock worth $25, and should be just as happy.[2]In contract law, that is t=
he=C2=A0normal=C2=A0remedy for breach of contract. It is called =E2=80=9Cex=
pectation damages.=E2=80=9D If Musk signed a deal to buy a thing for $54.20=
, and then he refused to pay and had no good reason for backing out of the =
deal, and the seller had to turn around and sell the thing to someone else =
for $25 instead, then the seller could go to court and demand that Musk pay=
 the $29.20 difference.=C2=A0Merger agreements are contracts, and in theory=
=C2=A0a jilted seller could sue a buyer for expectation damages, but in pra=
ctice merger agreements often=C2=A0limit the availability of damages. In pa=
rticular, the Twitter merger agreement (Section 8.3(c)) says that Twitter c=
an=E2=80=99t get more than $1 billion of damages from Musk, which is also t=
he amount of the reverse=C2=A0termination fee that Musk has to pay Twitter =
in certain circumstances.[3]So if Musk has no good reason to walk away from=
 the deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I think he obviously does not, though he=E2=80=
=99ll=C2=A0argue otherwise in court =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Twitter sues him for=
 damages, it can=E2=80=99t get more than $1 billion. Its=C2=A0actual=C2=A0e=
xpectation damages are something like $24 billion. The capped damages are n=
owhere close to enough to compensate Twitter for the lost deal.But, as we d=
iscussed on=C2=A0Saturday, Twitter has a better option. It=C2=A0can sue for=
 specific performance, and ask a Delaware judge to order Musk to pay, not $=
1 billion or $24 billion, but the whole $44 billion=C2=A0to actually close =
the deal and buy Twitter.[4] This is more fraught and complicated than suin=
g for damages; specific performance is not the most normal remedy in contra=
ct law, and for reasons we  discussed on Saturday=C2=A0there are lots of re=
asons that it might be particularly difficult here. Forcing a guy to buy a =
company that he doesn=E2=80=99t want is a very drastic move, and nobody rea=
lly=C2=A0wants=C2=A0to do it. But the merger agreement does say that Twitte=
r is entitled to specific performance of Musk=E2=80=99s obligations, and th=
at each party =E2=80=9Cagrees that it will not oppose the granting of an in=
junction, specific performance and other equitable relief on the basis that=
 any other=C2=A0party has an adequate remedy at law or that any award of sp=
ecific performance is not an appropriate remedy for any reason at law or in=
 equity.=E2=80=9DAnd so, if this dispute ends up in court, there are three =
things that the court can do:=09Agree with Musk, and let him terminate the=
=C2=A0deal without paying anything.[5]=09Agree with Twitter that Musk is bo=
und by his contract, and then make him pay $1 billion, the maximum availabl=
e damages, for breaching the contract.=09Agree with Twitter that Musk is bo=
und by his contract, and then order specific performance, making him pay $4=
4 billion to actually buy Twitter.I will ignore the first possibility, not =
only because I think it is unlikely but also because it is=C2=A0functionall=
y the same as the second. On the scale of Twitter=E2=80=99s market capitali=
zation, or of Musk=E2=80=99s wealth, letting Musk walk away for $0 is not m=
eaningfully different from letting him walk away for $1 billion. In either =
case, Musk is fine, and Twitter is not.=C2=A0So=C2=A0the possible outcomes =
of litigation are extremely binary: He pays $44 billion and buys Twitter, o=
r he pays zero-to-$1-billion and does not. And there is nothing in between.=
 A court can=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=9Cman, this is really bad, but I am not g=
oing to force you to buy Twitter because that seems cruel to everyone, so I=
 will make you pay $10 billion of damages to compensate Twitter and send a =
message.=E2=80=9D Nope! It=E2=80=99s $44 billion or $1 billion.Also, though=
, the possible outcomes of litigation are extremely=C2=A0terrible. Letting =
the world=E2=80=99s richest person get out of a deal for a nominal fee beca=
use he got bored with it undermines the rule of law and the predictability =
of Delaware merger agreements. But forcing an unwilling buyer to own a=C2=
=A0big public company =E2=80=94=C2=A0with thousands of employees and an out=
sized influence on politics and culture =E2=80=94 seems bad for the buyer, =
the employees, the users and the world.=C2=A0Nobody wants either of these o=
utcomes.[6] But they are the only available outcomes in court.Now: They are=
 not the only possible outcomes in the=C2=A0world. They are the only possib=
le outcomes in=C2=A0court. If Twitter and Musk go to court and fight to the=
 death and a court enters a final judgment, it will be for one of those thi=
ngs, $1 billion or $44 billion. But because the outcomes are so drastically=
 different, and so binary, and so=C2=A0bad, and because no one is entirely=
=C2=A0sure which one it will be, the two sides have a lot of incentive to t=
ry to=C2=A0settle=C2=A0for something in between.There are two possible sort=
s of settlement:=09Musk buys Twitter for less, or=09Musk walks away for mor=
e.Musk and Twitter could agree that he will close the deal, but will pay le=
