 Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters =
here. Thanks![1]=C2=A0Twitter=E2=80=99s stock closed at $35.27 per share th=
e day before Musk started buying it in January, so that is in a sense the u=
naffected price of the stock. Since then the market, and the social-media i=
ndustry, and Twitter=E2=80=99s business have not done so great, and Musk ha=
s spent a lot of time specifically undermining Twitter. The stock closed at=
 $36.81 on Friday, reflecting some probability of the deal with Musk closin=
g at $54.20 per share and some probability of it not doing that. It opened =
at $34.60 this morning, after Musk said he=E2=80=99d try to get out of the =
deal and Twitter said he couldn=E2=80=99t. Incidentally if you want Twitter=
=E2=80=99s bankers=E2=80=99 views on Twitter=E2=80=99s stand-alone value as=
 of April 25, you can find them on pages 67-68, 70-71, 78 and=C2=A079-80 he=
re.=C2=A0[2] Obviously these things are not complete equivalents. In partic=
ular,=C2=A0I am ignoring tax consequences.=C2=A0[3] It can=E2=80=99t get bo=
th the fee and damages; the cap is $1 billion, not $2 billion. =E2=80=9CIn =
no event shall Equity Investor, Parent or Acquisition Sub collectively be s=
ubject to an aggregate amount for monetary damages (including any payment o=
f the Parent Termination Fee) in excess of an aggregate amount equal to the=
 Parent Termination Fee,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0says the agreement.[4] I am saying $=
44 billion for simplicity (that=E2=80=99s the deal value that  Bloomberg re=
ports). Actually it is more complicated: Musk would have to put up $33.5 bi=
llion of his own equity commitment, along with $13 billion of debt financin=
g from his banks; Twitter could only get specific performance if the debt f=
inancing is available. (Note that $44 billion is almost, but not quite, $33=
.5 billion plus $13 billion, for reasons that are not especially important =
here.) We discussed this issue on Saturday and I will not rehash it here; I=
 am just going to shorthand this as making Musk pay $44 billion.=C2=A0[5]=
=C2=A0There are scenarios in which Twitter could have to pay a $1 billion t=
ermination fee to Musk, but none of them are relevant here. That=E2=80=99s =
basically if Twitter terminates the deal to take a better offer from someon=
e else; it won=E2=80=99t. There is no scenario where Musk goes to court and=
 says =E2=80=9CI want out of this deal because of bots=E2=80=9D and the jud=
ge says =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=99re right, you poor dear, Twitter really misled=
 you about those bots, I will make *them* pay *you* a billion dollars.=E2=
=80=9D[6]=C2=A0Another bad thing about fighting to death in court is that i=
t is expensive, since you have to pay a lot of lawyers. Yesterday  Bloomber=
g reported that Twitter had hired Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & Katz (disclosur=
e: where I used to work), while Musk has hired Quinn Emanuel Urquhart & Sul=
livan LLP, and they are not cheap. Be a little careful with this one, thoug=
h. Litigating to the death is expensive for Musk, since he has to pay lawye=
rs. It is expensive for Twitter if it loses (that is, if it doesn=E2=80=99t=
 get specific performance), since it has to pay lawyers. But if Twitter *wi=
ns*, and a court orders Musk to close the deal at $54.20, and he does, then=
 effectively *Musk* is paying Twitter=E2=80=99s legal bills: The legal fees=
 come out of Twitter=E2=80=99s cash on hand, and now Musk owns Twitter and =
pays shareholders $54.20 per share without deducting those legal fees. So T=
witter does not exactly have incentives to be economical with lawyers, if i=
t thinks it has a good case.[7] Dave Hoffman, a law professor at Penn, has =
a good Twitter thread about this, arguing that =E2=80=9Cthe court will want=
 Musk's team to think that she will grant [specific performance], but will =
also desperately hope the case settles=E2=80=9D: Settling for a large amoun=
t of money to avoid an order of specific performance is strictly better tha=
n ordering specific performance. He adds=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Cthe best result=
 for everyone except for Twitter's shareholders is a monetary settlement, a=
t somewhere between $1 and $10B.=E2=80=9D
