<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Oh Elon</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One question that might be important i=
s: How much is Twitter Inc. worth if Elon Musk does=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>=
buy it? If Twitter announced today =E2=80=9Cwe have agreed to terminate our=
 deal with Elon Musk with no money changing hands, never mind,=E2=80=9D wha=
t would happen to the stock? Well, it would go down.=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t k=
now how much. But just to put a number on it, let=E2=80=99s assume that it =
would trade to $25 per share,=C2=A0that that is Twitter=E2=80=99s stand-alo=
ne value.[1] That is not investing advice or even a real estimate, but it=
=E2=80=99s helpful to have a placeholder.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A=
t Musk=E2=80=99s $54.20 deal price, Twitter is worth about $44 billion; at =
$25 it would be worth about $20 billion. The difference is $24 billion, or =
$29.20 per share. Musk is paying $24 billion over Twitter=E2=80=99s stand-a=
lone value. Or he isn=E2=80=99t. In April he agreed to pay $44 billion to b=
uy Twitter; last Friday he announced that he will try to get out of the dea=
l. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28338609.272=
590/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMDk=
vZWxvbi1zLW91dD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzExMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJn=
V0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA3MTEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c=
3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1286f227/email" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about this =
on Saturday</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Note that Twitter should, =
in theory, be indifferent between (1) closing the deal and (2) getting a ch=
eck from Musk=C2=A0for $24 billion. If Musk paid Twitter the $24 billion=C2=
=A0difference in cash, Twitter could pay it out as a dividend to its shareh=
olders. Instead of having $54.20 in cash, they=E2=80=99d have $29.20 in cas=
h and a share of stock worth $25, and should be just as happy.[2]</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In contract law, that is the=C2=A0<em>normal=C2=A0</=
em>remedy for breach of contract. It is called =E2=80=9Cexpectation damages=
.=E2=80=9D If Musk signed a deal to buy a thing for $54.20, and then he ref=
used to pay and had no good reason for backing out of the deal, and the sel=
ler had to turn around and sell the thing to someone else for $25 instead, =
then the seller could go to court and demand that Musk pay the $29.20 diffe=
rence.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Merger agreements are contract=
s, and in theory=C2=A0a jilted seller could sue a buyer for expectation dam=
ages, but in practice merger agreements often=C2=A0limit the availability o=
f damages. In particular, the Twitter merger agreement (<a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28338609.272590/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjL=
mdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTgwOTEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyMTc2NzUzL2QyODMx=
MTlkcHJlcjE0YS5odG0jYW54YXRvYzI4MzExOV83Nw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc1cabba=
9/email" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">Section 8.3(c)</a>) says that Twitter can=E2=80=99t get mo=
re than $1 billion of damages from Musk, which is also the amount of the re=
verse=C2=A0termination fee that Musk has to pay Twitter in certain circumst=
ances.[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So if Musk has no good reason to =
walk away from the deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I think he obviously does not, t=
hough he=E2=80=99ll=C2=A0argue otherwise in court =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Twitte=
r sues him for damages, it can=E2=80=99t get more than $1 billion. Its=C2=
=A0<em>actual=C2=A0</em>expectation damages are something like $24 billion.=
 The capped damages are nowhere close to enough to compensate Twitter for t=
he lost deal.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, as we discussed on=C2=A0=
Saturday, Twitter has a better option. It=C2=A0can sue for specific perform=
ance, and ask a Delaware judge to order Musk to pay, not $1 billion or $24 =
billion, but the whole $44 billion=C2=A0to actually close the deal and buy =
Twitter.[4] This is more fraught and complicated than suing for damages; sp=
ecific performance is not the most normal remedy in contract law, and for r=
easons we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28338609=
.272590/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDc=
tMDkvZWxvbi1zLW91dD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzExMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYW=
lsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA3MTEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vb=
mV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC1286f227/email" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> discussed on S=
aturday</a>=C2=A0there are lots of reasons that it might be particularly di=
fficult here. Forcing a guy to buy a company that he doesn=E2=80=99t want i=
s a very drastic move, and nobody really=C2=A0<em>wants=C2=A0</em>to do it.=
 But the merger agreement <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/28338609.272590/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXR=
hLzE0MTgwOTEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyMTc2NzUzL2QyODMxMTlkcHJlcjE0YS5odG0jYW54YXRvYz=
I4MzExOV85MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB91b6e175/email" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">does <em>say<=
/em></a> that Twitter is entitled to specific performance of Musk=E2=80=99s=
 obligations, and that each party =E2=80=9Cagrees that it will not oppose t=
he granting of an injunction, specific performance and other equitable reli=
ef on the basis that any other=C2=A0party has an adequate remedy at law or =
that any award of specific performance is not an appropriate remedy for any=
 reason at law or in equity.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And s=
o, if this dispute ends up in court, there are three things that the court =
can do:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margi=
n: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Agree with Musk, and let h=
im terminate the=C2=A0deal without paying anything.[5]</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Agree with Twitter that Musk is bound by his contract,=
 and then make him pay $1 billion, the maximum available damages, for breac=
hing the contract.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Agree with Twit=
ter that Musk is bound by his contract, and then order specific performance=
, making him pay $44 billion to actually buy Twitter.</li></ol><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">I will ignore the first possibility, not only because I th=
ink it is unlikely but also because it is=C2=A0<em>functionally the same as=
 the second. </em>On the scale of Twitter=E2=80=99s market capitalization, =
or of Musk=E2=80=99s wealth, letting Musk walk away for $0 is not meaningfu=
lly different from letting him walk away for $1 billion. In either case, Mu=
sk is fine, and Twitter is not.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So=C2=
=A0the possible outcomes of litigation are extremely binary: He pays $44 bi=
llion and buys Twitter, or he pays zero-to-$1-billion and does not. And the=
re is nothing in between. A court can=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=9Cman, this is r=
eally bad, but I am not going to force you to buy Twitter because that seem=
s cruel to everyone, so I will make you pay $10 billion of damages to compe=
nsate Twitter and send a message.=E2=80=9D Nope! It=E2=80=99s $44 billion o=
r $1 billion.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, though, the possible ou=
tcomes of litigation are extremely=C2=A0<em>terrible</em>. Letting the worl=
d=E2=80=99s richest person get out of a deal for a nominal fee because he g=
ot bored with it undermines the rule of law and the predictability of Delaw=
are merger agreements. But forcing an unwilling buyer to own a=C2=A0big pub=
lic company =E2=80=94=C2=A0with thousands of employees and an outsized infl=
uence on politics and culture =E2=80=94 seems bad for the buyer, the employ=
ees, the users and the world.=C2=A0Nobody wants either of these outcomes.[6=
] But they are the only available outcomes in court.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Now: They are not the only possible outcomes in the=C2=A0<em>worl=
d</em>. They are the only possible outcomes in=C2=A0<em>court</em>. If Twit=
ter and Musk go to court and fight to the death and a court enters a final =
judgment, it will be for one of those things, $1 billion or $44 billion. Bu=
t because the outcomes are so drastically different, and so binary, and so=
=C2=A0bad, and because no one is entirely=C2=A0sure which one it will be, t=
he two sides have a lot of incentive to try to=C2=A0<em>settle=C2=A0</em>fo=
r something in between.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two possi=
ble sorts of settlement:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-=
left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Musk buys=
 Twitter for less, or</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Musk walks a=
way for more.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk and Twitter could =
agree that he will close the deal, but will pay less than $54.20 per share.=
 I don=E2=80=99t know what the number is. More than the $25ish per share th=
at I have been assuming Twitter is worth without Musk. More, probably, than=
 the $36.81 closing price of Twitter on Friday, before Musk tried to get ou=
t of the deal. These sorts of renegotiations happen sometimes and usually r=
esult in=C2=A0pretty modest price cuts, but it is hard at this point to ima=
gine Musk agreeing to pay, like, $52.69. He will want a big price cut ($35?=
) and Twitter will want a small one ($52?) and it might be hard to reach ag=
reement.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If they do, though, they will sign=
